      <hedline>
        <hl1>Let the Defense Debate Begin</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael W Brandriss letter disputes August 21 editorial on rebuidling of US defenses for 21st Century</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 21 editorial ''Defense in the 21st Century'' describes the assumption that our military forces might have to fight two regional wars simultaneously as ''highly improbable'' and later as ''highly unlikely.'' Viewed as pure coincidence, this may be correct.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Aug. 21 editorial ''Defense in the 21st Century'' describes the assumption that our military forces might have to fight two regional wars simultaneously as ''highly improbable'' and later as ''highly unlikely.'' Viewed as pure coincidence, this may be correct.</p>
        <p>But a potential adversary, finding us engaged in one regional conflict, would surely consider it an opportune time to risk engaging us in another conflict and might well have plans for such an eventuality. The odds against the possibility may be much smaller than you assume.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL W. BRANDRISS  Pittsford, N.Y., Aug. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
